To get minimal steps, we can think of covering distance by taking maximum jumps towards Y and then come back. But this doesn’t give minimum steps to us.
As we keep jumping towards right, our jump size keeps doubling. We can end up jumping very far away from Y in last jump  and we can loose minimal steps.

But if we go back, from Y to X, then 
(1.) we would have utilised our biggest jump i.e. last jump to reach Y. And 
(2.) our jump size also keeps decreasing, so even if we land very far way to left of X, then also it would give us minimal steps when we move forward to Y.

**Recursive**
```
    public int brokenCalc(int X, int Y) {
        if(Y <= X) return X-Y;
        return 1 + (Y % 2 == 0 ? brokenCalc(X, Y/2) : brokenCalc(X, Y + 1));
    }
```
**Iterative**
```
    public int brokenCalc(int X, int Y) {
        int ans = 0;
        for(; Y > X ;  Y = Y % 2 > 0 ? Y + 1 : Y / 2, ans++);
        return (ans + X - Y);
    }
```

