solutions.content:
Here is a approach that works from start to end.
**Working:**
1. Keep on multiplying start with 2 until start >= target, meanwhile also calculate the steps.
2. Now we have to remove the difference we have between start and target, from the examples you already know reducing at the end wont work.
**Here is the logic part:**
To reduce the difference , if we had reduced 1 in any previous step, it would have got multiplied with power of 2s till now. SO using the step count , we can reduced the biggest possible 2's power from difference
Lets see with example 
**start = 3 , end = 18
 3 -> 6 -> 12 -> 24   steps=4;**
 difference = 24-18 = 6
 Now we have to reduce this 6 to 0.

 If we reduced -1 when x=3 , it would have become -8 till which we cant subtract from 6.
 If we reduced -1 when x=6 , it would have become -4 , which we can include. SO now diff = 6-4=2;
 Now we need to reduce 2, when x is in 3phase i.e 12 (although it doesnt mean value would be 12 as we have modifed values in previous iterations) -1 will be become -2 in end and diff=0;

```
class Solution {
public:
 int brokenCalc(int startValue, int target) {
     if(startValue >= target)
         return startValue-target;
	long long  x = startValue;
	int steps = 0;
	while (x < target)
		x *= 2, steps++;
	long long diff =  x - target;
	if (diff==0) return steps;
	int i = steps;
	while ( diff != 0) {
		if (diff - (1<<i) >= 0) {
			diff -= (1<<i);
			steps++;
		}
        else
		i--;
	}
	return steps;
}
};
```

