solutions.content:
Here's what approach I used -
* Let's start to reach from target to startValue since it'll also take same steps to reach startValue from target.
* The operations will change here. for **startValue = startValue*2 -> target = target/2** and for **startValue = startValue - 1 -> target = target + 1.**
* The first case is when starting value is equal to target, then there is no step involved here to change values, so simply return 0.
* Then we started our steps from 0 and Performed these operations until our target is greater than startValue -
  1. The first case is when my **target value is even**, then one operation can be performed -> **target = target/2** ( so for startValue, it'll be startValue = startValue*2 that is allowed Operation by the calculator.)
  2. If **my target is odd**, then we can only perform **target = (target + 1**) operation since doing target = target/2 operation will give us float value that isn't allowed here. ( For the startValue, This operation will be startValue = startValue - 1 )
* Now loop will only break in 2 conditons, either my target is less than startValue or target is equal to startValue.
* If target is less than startValue, then doing operations target = target/2 isn't going to help. so the only Beneficial operation here is target = target + 1.
* We'll do this target = target+1 operation to fill the difference between target and startValue so for **(startValue - target)** times. 
* In the case when target is equal to startValue, this difference (startValue - target) will be zero.
* so we'll simply add these extra steps required to our steps variable.
* Now steps variable contains minimum steps needed to reach from startValue to target.


```
class Solution {
public:
    int brokenCalc(int startValue, int target) {
	/* Since startValue = target, no step required to change value */
        if(startValue == target) return 0;

		/* starting value of steps = 0 */
        int steps = 0;
        while(target>startValue){
		/* If target value is even, we can only do this operation */
            if( target%2==0){
                target=target/2;
            }
			/* In case of odd value */
            else target+=1;

			/* steps will increase in both cases */
            steps++;
        }

		/* our target might have become less than startValue by target = target/2 operation so add the difference here
		 that shows the number of times we will perform target = target+1 */
        steps+=(startValue-target);

		/* Final minimum steps required */
        return steps;
    }
};
```

